{
  "analysis": "We are in /app with a compiled binary called mystery. No investigation has been done yet. We need to determine the binary's behavior and write a small C implementation mystery.c that reproduces it exactly when compiled with gcc -static -o reversed mystery.c -lm && ./reversed.",
  "plan": "First inspect the file type, strings, symbols, and basic behavior of /app/mystery. Run file, ls, strings, and a few sample executions to understand inputs/outputs. This will guide whether it is a simple filter, calculator, or something else.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "ls -la /app\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "file /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "strings -a /app/mystery | head -100\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "printf '1\\n2\\n' | /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "printf 'hello\\n' | /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The mystery binary appears to ignore stdin and prints a fixed sequence of messages about rendering an 800x600 image and writing image.ppm. The `file` command is unavailable. We need to inspect the exact stdout output, any files it creates, and potentially disassemble/decompile it to reproduce the exact behavior, especially the PPM file contents.",
  "plan": "Run the binary in a clean temp directory to see what files it creates, capture exact stdout/stderr, inspect image.ppm size and header, and look for more useful strings/symbols. Also check available tools like objdump, readelf, nm, xxd, od for further analysis.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "mkdir -p /tmp/mtest && cd /tmp/mtest && rm -f * && /app/mystery >out.txt 2>err.txt; echo EXIT:$?; ls -la; echo '---OUT---'; xxd out.txt | head -50; echo '---ERR---'; xxd err.txt | head -50\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && echo '---PPM HEAD---'; xxd image.ppm | head -20; echo '---PPM SIZE---'; wc -c image.ppm\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "readelf -h /app/mystery\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "nm /app/mystery 2>/dev/null | head -80 || true\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "strings -a /app/mystery | grep -Ei 'ppm|image|render|progress|ffmpeg|800|600|done|wrote|error|fopen|main|float|double|sin|cos|sqrt' | head -100\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "The mystery binary writes messages to stderr (not stdout) and creates image.ppm. stdout was empty. The PPM file is 5362624 bytes, which is larger than a simple 800x600x3 P6 image (1440015 bytes), so the actual image dimensions/content need investigation. xxd is unavailable, so we need od/head/odc. We also need to inspect the exact stderr content.",
  "plan": "Use od and head to inspect err.txt and the beginning of image.ppm. Check how many progress lines stderr contains. Use nm/objdump to locate main and write_image and disassemble them. Also check if the PPM is binary P6 or ASCII P3.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && echo '---ERR CONTENT---'; cat err.txt; echo '---ERR BYTES---'; wc -c err.txt; echo '---ERR LINES---'; wc -l err.txt\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && echo '---PPM HEAD OCTAL---'; od -A x -t x1z image.ppm | head -20\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && echo '---PPM FIRST CHARS---'; head -c 80 image.ppm | od -c\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /tmp/mtest && echo '---ERR TAIL---'; tail -20 err.txt\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "nm /app/mystery | grep -E ' T main$| write_image| render| T [a-z]' | head -50\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery | grep -A2 '<main>:' | head -10\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}

{
  "analysis": "Mystery is a statically-linked ray tracer. It writes stderr messages and an ASCII P3 PPM image.ppm of 800x600. Symbols reveal vector/ray/sphere/plane/trace/write_image functions. We need exact pixel values. The PPM starts with 159 197 255 and transitions to 158 197 255, indicating a gradient/image. Next step is to disassemble main and rendering functions to recover the scene and math.",
  "plan": "Disassemble main, allocate_image, write_image, trace, sphere_intersect, plane_intersect, sky_color, is_in_shadow, vector functions, ray_create/ray_at to reconstruct the C source. Also dump constants near rodata/data that define sphere/plane/light/camera parameters.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery --start-address=0x401740 --stop-address=0x401b80\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery --start-address=0x402c30 --stop-address=0x402de0\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery --start-address=0x402de0 --stop-address=0x402e50\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery --start-address=0x402750 --stop-address=0x402c30\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "objdump -d /app/mystery --start-address=0x401fd0 --stop-address=0x402750\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    }
  ]
}
